<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Stunning is very high agro, and chain stunning will get you hurt if you aren't careful. I didn't use stuns for a long time, but now I try to toss in a few stuns when I have plenty of mana. Hard-hitting and caster mobs mobs tend to get a few extra stuns to prevent damage. When my group has two clerics, I try to arrange it so one heals and the other stuns and things work out well. Stunning is also a good way to stop runners if you don't have snare.<P>Here are some tips on avoiding agro from stuns:<P>1. Don't stun as soon as your puller gets back. Let them build up some hate.<BR>2. Make sure your tanks are taunting.<BR>3. If your stun is resisted, don't sit down immediately. Sitting is a taunt, and will increase your chances of drawing the mob off the tank. You might also back away some after a resisted stun. If your stun isn't resisted, your tanks should do enough damage while the mob is stunned to keep agro.<P>Try timing your stuns so you cast between med pulses. If a mob is hitting on a caster, try tossing a stun on the mob to stop damage until the tank can taunt it off. Only use your lowest level stun on a mob a chanter is attempting to mez. A higher level stun will do damage and break the mez.<P>Anybody else have suggestions on using stuns?<P>An interesting but unconventional group would be several clerics, a chanter, and a rogue. The clerics and chanter keep the mob stunned while the rogue backstabs.
</FONT>
