<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Let's say I have ONLY a warrior and a chanter to worry about for heals. The warrior has 4k+ hps buffed, the enchanter has half that. The warrior has 1200 ac or so buffed. The enchanter is around 1000.<P>Additionally, the warrior has a much higher defense skill, dodge, parry, riposte and other attributes that passively reduce the amount of damage each hit from a mob does.<P>So for each swing the mob makes against these chars, the warrior will take far less damage, and has a higher buffer if I'm "late" on a heal.<P>I normally have 3 heals loaded at any one time. Complete heal, remedy or divine light, and celestial.<P>Complete heal takes 400 mana in 10 seconds and heals whatever damage is done.<P>Remedy takes 174 mana in 3 seconds and heals 433 hps of damage. <P>Divine Light takes 350 mana in 4.5 seconds and heals 880 hps of damage.<P>Celestial takes 225 mana in 4 second cast and heals 744 points over 24 seconds.<P>That means that for a 4k hp tank getting healed at a half-bub a Complete heal heals about 3000hps/400mana = 7.5 hps per point of mana in 10 seconds. DL does 880/350 or 2.5 hps per point of mana in 4.5 seconds. Remedy does 433/175 or 2.4 hps per point of mana but only takes 3 seconds (frequently making it the better spell choice!) And celestial does 744/255 2.9 hps per point of mana but takes almost 30 seconds to do it!<P>This all means that using a complete heal on a 3k tank is ALWAYS more mana efficient than doing any heal on a chanter.<P>When I cast a C-Heal on a 4k tank at 1.5 bubs of health, I'm timing it so that it lands just in time to heal as many hps as possible and let me get back to meditating. I am being mana efficient - I get far more points of health per point of mana with this heal than with any other - and I am being time efficient, as I will likely have med'ed back almost all of those 400 mana points by the time I have to toss it out again. Additionally, if I fizzle a cast, mistarget, or otherwise "goof up" I have a large margine of error. The rate at which the tank is taking damage means I can fizzle multiple times and still save the day - just remedy to buy time to C-heal if the tank is too low. There is next to no risk involved here.<P>When I cast a remedy on a chanter I am not being mana efficient. I can't "time" a remedy due to the chanter's combination of low hps, low ac and low/non-existant defense skills I have to toss out those 175 mana the instant hte chanter starts to take damage. Even then, against a mob quading for 100 a shot and hitting 4 out of 4, the chanter will probably be going down fast in spite of my best efforts. To help the chanter out I'll land the first remedy and then cast a non-damage dealing stun on the mob to give the chanter time to regain control. More mana I spend and more time I spend not med'ing. After the stun I will still need to cast a celestial heal on the chanter in case he hasn't regained control and to fill the hp bar back up since they are still down a bub of health even after the remedy.<P>I have used MORE mana, when that is said and done, than a complete heal. I have had to use about as much time as a complete heal. And we have exposed our group to more risk than if it was the tank taking the damage. Because at the rate at which the chanter takes damage, a fizzle or a mistarget means the chanter is dead. The level of risk is very high.<P>All this means is that it is far far far far easier to heal the warrior than it is to heal the chanter.<P>Xp'ing is all about efficiency. Using the least amount of mana and time to kill the most mobs. Chanter hps cost more mana than warrior hps. Chanter hps take more time (as odd as that seems at first glance) than warrior hps. Chanter hps are riskier than warrior hps.<P>I want chanters to take as little damage as possible.
</FONT>
