<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Depends on the aggro really.  If the stun makes you have aggro the rest of the fight and thus brings you down to a couple of bubbles of health-dont do it!  Something you have to consider also is casting time.  Enchanters will go down fast-this is a fact.  So..if you're talking about 50+ mobs, a cleric may or may not even be able to throw a heal on you if you catch aggro.  Best thing for you to do if you want to take a more active role is slow the mobs!  Slow is a clerics best friend!<P>But generally speaking, healing the tank is easier on the mana as we can let the tank go down as far as we allow (personally, its 2 bubbles for me-to prevent accidents) before throwing a complete heal on them.  During that time (especially if the mob is slowed), we get a chance to med back whatever mana we have used.<P>Given the chance between healing the ench and healing the tank, I go for the ench everytime.  Dead ench=dead cleric=dead group.  But if the tank dies, the ench can always mes and the group run.  But you also have to consider that I am casting remedy for the speed of the heal for enchs.  If I have to cast that 50 times, I am going to be oom.  Best thing to do is avoid aggro as much as possible (I know thats not always an option with your spells) and let the tank keep the aggro.
</FONT>
